Abstract

Malaria models are routinely used in malaria research and policy, despite a great deal of uncertainty. Three important questions are:

  1. How well do we understand malaria in humans?

  2. Do we understand it well enough to give useful policy advice about malaria control?

  3. What makes a malaria model good? While there are many ways of being good, we care most about simulation-based analytics – using models to formulate malaria policy advice.

It is important to note that malaria models have already been used in policy. Ross developed the models to understand malaria transmission well enough to formulate coherent ideas about control [1–4]. Ross’s simple model – it would now be called an SIS compartment model – was used to help set the response timelines for the Global Malaria Eradication Programme [5,6].

Towards the end of the Global Malaria Eradication Programm (1966-1969), the Ross-Macdonald model was used to help design a malaria control trial in Kankiya District, northern Nigeria (1966-1969); the model predictions differed substantially from the results, leading to calls for a new mathematical model [7]. In short order, a new model had been developed with malaria immunity and some other features, and it was used to design a new trial in Garki, Nigeria (1972-73) [8]. The Garki model was innovative in two ways: it introduced new epidemiological states representing different stages of malaria immunity; and while Macdonald had formulated a flawed model of superinfection [9,10], but the Garki model found an elegant approximation. Shortly thereafter, Dutertre published a model that represented malaria infections using a different set of epidemiological states [11]. Since then, new models have been developed to address many aspects of malaria infection and immunity. The variety of models raises a question – what are the core mechanisms driving patterns in malaria epidemiology, and how should those mechanisms be represented in dynamical models?

Given our interest in policy, the ultimate goal is to identify the features of models that are realistic enough, and with enough skills to address the needs of malaria programs. Over the past century, models for policy have focused on malaria elimination, which emphasizes the suppression of transmission. As the emphasis has shifted to reducing the burden of malaria, there is a greater need to understand disease and mortality. Models for policy must be synthetic: they must address questions about exposure, infection, treatment, malaria burden, infectiousness, and detection. We want to do this without resorting to stochastic, individual-based models. Such models play an important role in malaria, but with so much stochasticity, the models are difficult to understand, critically evaluate, and use. We would like to develop a conceptual framework and an accompanying computational framework that allows us to clearly identify what is going wrong with the models, not to bring about paralysis, but to build ensembles of models that cover the uncertainty.

In this vignette, we review mathematical models for human malaria infections through 13 core concepts. Each concept is framed as a model that addresses one dimension of the complexity of malaria. Our core interest here is to develop models that can support malaria policy. The critical question, which we come to at the end, is what areas of uncertainty about malaria make the greatest difference?

Infection Dynamics

In 1899, Ronald Ross wrote enthusiastically about the extermination of malaria through mosquito control [12], and over the next decade, he devoted himself to The Prevention of Malaria [2–4]. As the malaria mosquito control programs saw some exciting successes, and some disappointing failures, Ross began to delve into a large and complex set of practical issues using mechanistic mathematical models. How much land would need to be cleared of mosquito habitat before malaria transmission would decline [1]? Ross developed the first mathematical model to understand malaria transmission, partly to answer Why did malaria mosquito control sometimes fail? The equations translated the quantitative logic governing malaria infection dynamics into a dynamical description of the prevalence of malaria infection in human populations (known then as the malaria rate or malaria parasite rate or parasite rate, PR). Ross was careful to make a distinction between local exposure and exposure acquired during travel, but the prevalence of infection was regarded as the balance between two dynamical processes:

  1. uninfected humans were becoming infected; and

  2. infected humans were clearing infections.

While Ross’s equations (most accessible in a 1911 Nature paper [13]) described malaria transmission dynamics and control, linking infections in humans and mosquitoes, this essay is focused on modeling malaria infections.

Meanwhile, Ross had also been interested in the measurement of malaria in populations. He developed the thick film to improve the accuracy of malaria diagnostics [14,15], and he described methods that could be used to measure transmission by mosquitoes [4]. These ideas all came together during the 1910s, as Ross attempted to establish the mathematical foundations for studying epidemics, for which he enlisted the help of Hilda Hudson, a Cambridge mathematician [16–19]. In those publications, the infection rate was called the happenings rate (\(h\)). Nowadays, we would call it the force of infection (FoI).

In the model, a population (of \(H\) people) was sub-divided into people who were either infected (\(X\)) or not (\(H-X\)). The rate that new infections would occur in a population was \(h(H-X).\) Ross assumed infections would clear at a constant rate, \(r\), so the net rate of clearance was \(rX\). The density of infected humans was described by an equation:

\[\frac{dX}{dt} = h(t) (H-X)-rX\] In mathematical epidemiology, dynamical systems are often used to model the annual dynamics of acute immunizing infections. In those epidemics, as people acquire lifelong immunity, a critical limiting factor is the size of the susceptible population.

In malaria, immunity does not provide strong protection against new infections, so malaria is highly prevalent. Seasonal fluctuations are mainly driven by mosquito population fluctuations, and without the depletion of susceptibles, malaria tends to be highly endemic. In places where transmission doesn’t vary enormously from year to year, we say that malaria transmission is stable, even if in places where transmission is highly seasonal. In some places, malaria transmission is unstable, which means that there are strong inter-annual fluctuations in exposure with marked changes in the incidence and prevalence of malaria. For malaria, the dynamics might have some tendency to cycle, but when we observe seasonality in malaria prevalence, we generally look at mosquito ecology as the most likely explanation. In this equation, the FoI is assumed to be a function of the EIR. One of the main reasons we work with differential equations is to understand the factors that determine scaling relationships between exposure, malaria prevalence and the incidence of disease.

In this model, true prevalence of infection over time is defined by the formula:

\[x(t) = \frac{X(t)}{H}.\] NOTE: This was not how Ross wrote it, but the two models are essentially identical.

Steady States

To analyze Ross’s equation, we do something very sensible. Instead of trying to grapple with the full complexity, we start simple. Suppose that \(h(t)\) is constant. In this case, the equation reaches a steady state when \(dX/dt = 0.\)

If \(h(t)\) is constant over time, then the true prevalence of infection in this model, \(x=X/H\), reaches a steady state that is a simple function of the parameters. Over time, the prevalence of infection reaches a steady state:

\[x = \frac{h}{h+r}\] The odds of infection in this model are given by a simple ratio: \[\frac{x}{1-x} = \frac{h}{r}\]

Having set up the model, we can examine the shape of a curve describing the steady state PR as a function of the FoI. Note that most of the variability, the informative range, occurs over values of the annualized FoI between about 1 and 10. On a semi-log plot, the relationship is sigmoidal. We save that this curve describes a scaling relationship, and we note that prevalence saturates as a function of the FoI.

Stable Orbits

While \(h(t)\) could be constant or seasonal, or it could vary in any way, a sensible next step for analysis is to analyze models with a canonical signal such that \(h(t+365) = h(t),\) then we do not get a stable state but a steady orbit. The following graph plots the stable orbits for two different canonical \(h(t)\) patterns with two different seasonal patterns and average values.

  • top left – The FoI patterns over a year; these are variants of trigonometric functions and power laws.

  • bottom left – The PR patterns. Note that the higher the FoI the higher the PR.

  • top right – The orbits. The mathematics were developed to understand the laws of planetary motion. By plotting the FoI vs. the PR, it might seem a bit more clear why we call these plots orbits.

  • bottom right – the idea of a steady state can shed some light on the orbits. In this graph, we have plotted the attractor as a maroon line. It is defined as the steady state that would be reached if the conditions at a point in time were to hold forever. One way to understand the dynamics is through the study of the attractor – the orbit is being pulled towards the attractor chasing it around the phase plane:

    • When the attractor is above the orbit, the orbit is increasing;

    • when the attractor is below the orbit, the orbit is decreasing.

    • Points where the orbits and the attractor intersect are critical points for the orbits (i.e. maxima or minima). This means that the PR is still rising, even after exposure has peaked, or that the PR is still falling early in the transmission season, even after exposure rates have started to rise again.

Since malaria is endemic, the focus of our analysis is on these steady states are

Age

In places where malaria transmission is stable, we can get a picture of malaria infection dynamics by looking at humans as they age. In effect we are using age as a surrogate for time. The dynamics look very similar (for Ross’s model):

\[\frac{dX}{da} = h(a) (H-X)-rX\]

but we can definitively establish an initial condition; since on one is born infected with malaria, we set \(X(0) = 0\). Now the dynamics describe how prevalence increases in cohorts as they age. The trick to aligning exposure is to establish the birth date of a cohort, \(\tau\) and then age is \(a = t-\tau.\) Using the same function we used for \(h(t)\), we can look at infection dynamics in infants as they age.

In the following, the black line represents the PR for a population exposed at a constant rate. The colored lines represent cohorts born 90 days apart. A critical feature of these plots are that prevalence rises somewhat slowly to the stable state. Later, in 11, we’ll introduce methods that make it possible to do time and age at the same time.

Critique

\(\oplus\)

Ross’s model for infection is as good a place as any to start. In today’s terms, Ross’s model for malaria infection dynamics of humans would be called an SIS compartmental model. If we want to study malaria or use models for analytics, there are several major issues that we must address. Each one of the twelve sections that follow addresses one of these concerns.

The SIS model

  • \(U\) - Uninfected

  • \(X\) - Infected

  • \(H=U+X\) - total population size

  • \(h\) - FoI

  • \(r\) - clearance rate

The first model

\[ \begin{array}{rl} \dot U &= - h U + r X\\ \dot X &= h U - r X \\ \end{array} \]

But since \(\dot U = - \dot X\), one of the equations is redundant.

Measuring Malaria

There are two big sets of metrics we need to consider: research metrics, and health systems metrics [20–22].

Research Metrics

  • The PfPR, the prevalence of malaria in cross-sectional blood surveys, is most commonly used research metric. Age-specific patterns in PfPR have been described for 27 datasets that reported PfPR highly stratified by age [23]. A common pattern in those datasets had several features: a rapid increase in prevalence with age, reaching a plateau sometime after age 2 and before age 5; a decline in prevalence starting around age 10 that continues through adolescence and into adulthood, such that the prevalence in adults is roughly 1/3 of the plateau.

  • The annual PfEIR and the seasonal pattern of the daily FoI.

  • The force of infection (FoI).

  • Serology.

Health Systems Metrics

  • Case Counts

  • TPR

State Space Modeling

To be useful in policy, we want to use simulation models to help us understand malaria transmission dynamics and control well enough to support decisions. Instead of regarding the models as abstract objects, we want to model malaria in some particular place in the recent past leading up to the present, and in the immediate future. We must think about the models as approximations of a particular messy and complex reality. We need an inferential framework. The reality we must confront is our inability to observe reality directly. Instead, we know about reality through an observational process that generates data. We learn about reality through the analysis of patterns in the data.

We regard these mechanistic models as approximations. In the state space modeling framework that we have adopted, the state variables, parameters, and terms in our mechanistic models are also not directly observable, so we call them latent states. We must be very specific about how these variables get translated into observable states through a model of the observational process. These observable states are what we are comparing to the malaria metrics (i.e., to data).

Superinfection

After Ross, the next

  • Queueing describes a queuing model for the MoI called \(M/M/\infty\)

  • Hybrid describes a queuing model for the MoI

Queueing

The queuing model of infection subdivides a population by MoI and tracks the transitions among states:

\[ \begin{array}{c} \begin{array}{ccccccccc} M_0 & {h\atop \longrightarrow} \atop {\longleftarrow \atop r} & M_1 & {h\atop \longrightarrow} \atop {\longleftarrow \atop {2r}} & M_2 & {h \atop \longrightarrow} \atop {\longleftarrow \atop {3r}} & M_3 & {h \atop \longrightarrow} \atop {\longleftarrow \atop {4r}}& \ldots \end{array} \\ \\ \begin{array}{rl} dM_0/dt &= -h M_0 + r M_1 \\ d M_i /dt &= -(h+r) M_i + h M_{i-1} + r(i+1) M_{i+1} \\ \end{array} \end{array} \]

A diagram of the queuing model \(M/M/\infty\) (top), and the master equations (bottom), in which \(M_i\) denotes the proportion of the population with MoI \(=i\). MoI increments by one if an infection occurs at rate \(h\) and decrements by one if an infection clears at rate \(ri\).

Liver Stages

This is effectively an \(SEI_1I_2\) model, where \(A = I_1\) and \(X=I_2.\)

\[ \begin{array}{rl} \dot E &= h U - \delta E\\ \dot A &= \delta E - \mu A\\ \dot X &= \mu A - r X\\ \end{array} \]

Acute & Chronic Phases

Or we can do it with delays:

\[ \begin{array}{rl} \dot A &= h_\mu(H - P) - \Upsilon \; h_\delta \left(H-P_\delta\right) \\ \end{array} \]

Treatment & Chemoprotection

Protection

  • \(P\) – uninfected and chemoprotected

  • \(\rho\) – treatment of primary fever

  • \(\zeta\) – treatment of secondary fever

  • \(\phi\) – background indiscriminate treatment

\[ \begin{array}{rl} \dot P &= (h \rho + \phi) (H-P) + \zeta X - \sigma P \\ \dot U &= r X + \sigma P - (h \rho + \phi) U \\ \dot X &= (1-\rho) h U - (r + h \rho + \zeta + \phi) X \\ \end{array} \]

Infectiousness

\[ \begin{array}{rl} \dot P &= (h \rho + \phi) (h \rho + \phi) U + \zeta X - \sigma P \\ \dot G &= (h \rho + \phi) (h \rho + \zeta + \phi) X + \zeta X - \sigma G \\ \dot U &= r X + \sigma P - (h \rho + \phi) U \\ \dot X &= (1-\rho) h U - (r + h \rho + \zeta + \phi) X \\ \end{array} \]

SoI

\(\oplus\)

Stage of Infection models subdivide infections into \(n\) stages.

  • Simple - A SoI model for simple infections

  • Super - A SoI model with superinfection

Simple

  • \(n\) is the number of stages

  • \(X_i\) is the density of the population with an infection in stage \(i\)

  • \(\nu_i\) is the rate an infection stages-up

  • \(r_i\) is the stage-specific clearance rate

\[ \begin{array}{rl} \dot U & = -h U + \sum r_i X_i \\ \dot X_1 & = h U - (r_1 + \nu_1) X_1 \\ \dot X_i & = \nu_{i-1} X_{i-1} - (h + r_i + \nu_i) X_i \\ \dot X_n & = \nu_{n-1} X_{n-1} - (h + r_n) X_n \\ \end{array} \] Note that this does not allow for the SoI to decrease. Such a model is possible.

Super

Here, we allow for over-writing superinfection:

  • \(X_i\) is the density with a lowest infected stage \(i\)

  • \(m_i\) is the mean multiplicity of infection for the \(i^{th}\) stage

  • Now \(\nu_i\) and \(r_i\) are functions of \(m_i\)

We develop a hybrid model to tracks the MoI in each stage:

\[ \begin{array}{rl} \dot m_1 & = h - (r_1 + \nu_1) m_1 \\ \dot m_i & = \nu_{i-1} m_{i-1} - (r_i + \nu_i) m_i \\ \dot m_n & = \nu_{n-1} m_{n-1} - (r_n + \nu_n) m_n \\ \end{array} \]

with dynamics:

\[ \begin{array}{rl} \dot U & = -h U + \sum r_i X_i \\ \dot X_1 & = h (H - X_1) - (r_1(m_1) + \nu_1(m_1)) X_1 \\ \dot X_i & = \nu_{i-1}(m_{i-1}) X_{i-1} - (h + r_i(m_i) + \nu_i(m_i)) X_i \\ \dot X_n & = \nu_{n-1}(m_{n-1}) X_{n-1} - (h + r_n(m_n)) X_n \\ \end{array} \]

Note is this exposing a weirdness in the model? Advancing to the next stage should depend on the stage-specific MoI.

Malaria Immunity

  • Stages – Stage-structured immunity (11)

  • Tracking – Modeling immunity with tracking variables (12)

  • Cohorts – Aging & Galerkin methods for cohort dynamics (13)

Stages

A mathematical model developed as part of the Garki Project [8] introduced the idea of modeling immunity in stages. A simpler version of the model was developed later by Klein, et al. [24]. Here, we present an even simpler version:

\[ \begin{array}{rl} \frac{dS_1}{da} &= B(t) + \theta S_2 - h S_1 + r_1 I_1 - \mu S_1\\ \frac{dI_1}{da} &= h S_1 - r_1 I_1 - \xi I_1 -\mu I_1 \\ \frac{dS_2}{da} &= h S_2 + r_2 I_2 - \theta S_2 - \mu S_2\\ \frac{dI_2}{da} &= \xi I_1 - h S_2 - r_2 I_2 - \mu I_2\\ \end{array} \]

Tracking

A model developed by Filipe introduced the idea of a tracking variable, a variable that tracks malaria exposure in a cohort as it ages [25]

\[ \begin{array}{rl} \dot P &= (h \rho(w) + \phi) (H-P) + \zeta(w) X - \sigma P \\ \dot U &= r X - (h \rho(w) + \phi) U \\ \dot X &= (1-\rho(w)) h U - (r + h \rho(w) + \zeta(w) + \phi) X \\ \dot w &= h - \xi w \end{array} \]

Relevant Detail

States

Age vs. PfPR

One of the dominant features of data describing malaria prevalence is a pattern with respect to age [23,26].

\[ \begin{array}{rl} \dot U & = -h U + \sum r_i X_i \\ \dot X_1 & = h (H - X_1) - (r_1 + \nu_1) X_1 \\ \dot X_i & = \nu_{i-1} X_{i-1} - (h + r_i + \nu_i) X_i \\ \dot X_n & = \nu_{n-1} X_{n-1} - (h + r_n) X_n \\ \dot w &= h - \xi w \end{array} \]

To investigate, we assume parasite densities are a function of stage and immunity, so the probability of detection is:

\[x = F_x(c_i X_i, w)\]

PDG model

We add an acute phase. We assume that the stages track acute stage infections, but a person can also carry an acute-stage infection. We introduce a chemo-protected state, \(P\), after treatment

  • \(A\) is the acute phase: any susceptible individual can be in both states;

  • Let \(\mu\) denote the duration of the latent period. We let \(h_\mu = h(t-\mu)\) denote the FoI at time \(t-\mu\) time units ago; the acute phase

  • Let \(\rho(w) A\) denote the treatment rate in response to a primary fever.

  • Let \(\zeta_i(w)\) denote the treatment rate in response to a secondary fever, by stage.

  • Let \(\phi\) denote the indiscriminate treatment rate.

\[ \begin{array}{rl} \dot P &= \left(\rho\left(w\right) A + \phi \right) \left(H-P\right) + \sum \zeta_i(w) X_i - \sigma P \\ \dot U & = \sigma P - \left(\rho\left(w\right) A + \phi \right) U - h_\delta U + \sum_i r_i X_i \\ \dot X_1 & = \Upsilon \; h_\delta \left(H -X_1\right) - \left(r_1 + \nu_1 + \zeta_1 (w) + \rho\left(w\right)A + \phi \right) X_1 \\ \dot X_i & = \nu_{i-1} X_{i-1} - \left(\Upsilon \; h_\delta + r_i + \nu_i + \zeta_i (w) + \rho\left(w\right)A + \phi \right) X_i \\ \dot X_n & = \nu_{n-1} X_{n-1} - \left(\Upsilon \; h_\delta + r_n + \zeta_n (w) + \rho\left(w\right)A + \phi \right) X_i \\ \dot A &= h_\mu(H - P_\mu) - \Upsilon \; h_\delta \left(H-P_\delta\right) \\ \dot w &= h - \xi w \end{array} \]

Where we use Sean’s trick to compute treatment during the acute phase, \(\Upsilon\)

\[ \dot \Upsilon = -\left[(\dot P + \sigma P)_\mu - (\dot P + \sigma P)_\delta \right]\Upsilon \]

and detection by light microscopy:

\[ c_A A + (1-c_A A) \sum_i c_i(w) X(w) \]

and detection by RDT?

Disease is subdivided into mild, moderate, and severe. Also, we need to make some kind of decision about how to handle anemia.

  • Severe We assume that most severe disease is associated with a primary fever \[\propto \rho(w)A\]

  • Moderate We assume that most moderate disease is associated with a primary fever or an early stage infection \[\propto \rho(w)A + \rho_1(w) X_1\]

  • Mild We assume that some mild disease is the result of a primary fever, but most mild disease arises from secondary fever \[\propto \rho(w)A + \sum_i \zeta_i(w) X_i\]
